prompt_template:
Create a {ASPECT_RATIO} image in the "Monochrome Grid Sneaker Tech Spec" visual style.

Subject: {SUBJECT}
Action: {SUBJECT_ACTION}
Prop/Product: {PRODUCT_OR_PROP}
Location: {LOCATION}
Background: {BACKGROUND_ELEMENTS}
Main text: {MAIN_TEXT}
Secondary text: {SECONDARY_TEXT}
Accent symbol: {ACCENT_SYMBOL}
Wardrobe/styling: {WARDROBE_STYLE}
Style fidelity anchors: {STYLE_FIDELITY_ANCHORS}
Source content to avoid: {SOURCE_CONTENT_TO_AVOID}

Apply these style rules as concrete visual requirements:
- Composition: one oversized logo-free footwear product in a three-quarter product angle, floating on a pale engineering grid; a narrow top band of small black-and-white evidence panels; two to four macro inset boxes connected by thin technical lines; sparse negative space and asymmetric editorial balance.
- Typography: pixelated uppercase product headline near the lower-left or lower-third area; tiny condensed uppercase feature captions; compact microtype; no copied slogans, no real brand marks, no social UI.
- Color: strict black, white, and gray palette; off-white paper field, deep black shadows, mid-gray halftone texture, pale grid lines; no color accent.
- Texture and lighting: coarse newspaper halftone, photocopy grain, scanner softness, hard monochrome product lighting, crisp shoe edges, soft contact shadow under the hero product.
- Graphic elements: crop marks, registration crosses, L-shaped brackets, measurement ticks, rectangular macro panels, fine connector lines, and small technical labels aligned to the grid.

Important content rule: match the style fidelity anchors first, then change the source content. Keep every sample about footwear, but use a new shoe silhouette, new product text, new material story, new top-strip panels, and new macro details. Do not include any visible Nike swoosh, adidas three-stripe mark, Puma logo, PEAK mark, watermark, QR code, username, or copied reference text.
